[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    13[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThis is the first recipe in the cookbook that lands at the "Complex" complexity tier in the chapter, and the writing meets the moment. The 3:14 a.m. medical-surgical-floor sepsis vignette (32-bed unit, two charge nurses sharing a CNA, 67-year-old post-op day 2 from colon resection, vitals charted at 11 p.m. as "mostly normal" by single-threshold rules, daughter pressing the call button at 1:40 a.m. with the patient confused, recollect K stayed at 4.2 from baseline because this is sepsis not pseudohyperkalemia, lactate 4.2, broad-spectrum antibiotics at 2:38 a.m., ICU at 4:15 a.m., nine extra days of stay and three weeks of inpatient rehab, and the data trail of HR climbing from 78 to 92 over eight hours, RR creeping from 14 to 18, temperature rising from 37.1 to 37.8, white count of 14.2, creatinine 0.3 above baseline, "patient appears slightly more somnolent than earlier shift, easily arousable" in the 9 p.m. nursing note) lands the operational reality of subclinical deterioration in three paragraphs. The closing question ("which patients on the floor right now are showing the early signs of deterioration, hours before they hit any single alarm threshold, so the team can intervene before the call button gets pressed at 1:40 a.m.") is the reframe most first-time builders miss and the recipe states it plainly.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    14[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    15[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe track-and-trigger lineage subsection is clinically accurate and pedagogically correct: MEWS as the original additive scoring system, NEWS and NEWS2 with the Royal College of Physicians provenance and the 2017 NEWS2 revision adding separate handling for chronic hypoxic respiratory disease, qSOFA as sepsis-specific, PEWS for pediatrics with parental concern as a formal criterion, SIRS as the older non-specific antecedent that hospital protocols still reference. The "score of 4 from two parameters slightly off is treated the same as a 4 from one parameter way off" framing is the kind of detail-level teaching that a senior hospitalist or rapid-response nurse would recognize. The "what ML adds (and where it adds less than vendors suggest)" subsection is the right pedagogical reframe: patient-specific baselines, trajectory awareness, multivariate fusion are real ML wins; replacing the underlying clinical reasoning or operational integration is not. The honest framing that "the vendor literature talks a lot about model performance and not enough about the workflow problem; the published peer-reviewed literature is more honest about it" sets up the rest of the recipe well.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    16[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    17[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe "two big vendor models, and why you should know their reputations" subsection is unusually candid. Naming Epic Deterioration Index and eCART by name, naming the 2021 Wong et al. external validation study and its finding that vendor-reported performance often doesn't match local-population performance, and the explicit "the right answer for many hospitals is to deploy a commercial model with strong local validation rather than build from scratch" framing is the design lesson most first-time builders miss. This subsection is the cookbook's first published treatment of vendor-versus-build for clinical ML, and the framing is correct. The HTML-comment TODO acknowledging the need to confirm the Wong et al. JAMA Internal Medicine citation and recent EDI external validation results is the right discipline.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    18[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    19[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe statistical and ML methods subsection is the broadest method survey in any chapter-3 recipe (logistic regression with engineered features, gradient-boosted trees, recurrent neural networks, transformer-based time series models, survival analysis, multi-task learning, phenotype-specific models, ensemble combinations). The "reasonable progression" closing posture (start with NEWS2 baseline, then engineered LR and GBT, then iterate, then add LSTM or transformer only if the marginal gain justifies the operational complexity) is the kind of operations-engineer voice the cookbook is built on. The outcome-definition subsection is unusually substantive: ICU transfer with the policy-variation caveat, cardiac arrest and code blue with the lower-base-rate caveat, composite endpoints with the phenotype-mixing caveat, mortality with the lagging-indicator caveat, phenotype-specific outcomes with the labeling-challenges caveat, time-windowed prediction with the operationally-useful framing. The closing "use a composite endpoint on a 6-24 hour prediction window with phenotype-specific stratification as a secondary analysis after the primary model is in production" is the practical guidance most published treatments dance around.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    20[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    21[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe features-that-actually-matter subsection has eleven feature classes (current vitals, vitals trajectory, vitals-derived composites including shock index and ROX index, recent labs, lab trajectory, medications including the active medication list and the recent administrations and the therapeutic class, patient context, unit context, nursing assessments with explicit Rothman Index reference, patient-specific baselines, time since admission, order patterns) and the closing posture ("a useful model has 50-200 features. More is not better") is the right scoping. The "the team has just ordered a lactate" feature being one of the highest-importance features in production models is the kind of texture that distinguishes the cookbook from documentation. The sampling-time-windows-and-right-censoring subsection correctly names time-grid snapping, prediction window construction with the patient-level train/test split, right censoring with the survival-modeling alternative, event leakage with the 30-60 minute lookahead boundary, and treatment leakage with the antibiotics-versus-deterioration confounding. Treatment leakage in particular is the single most consequential modeling concern the recipe identifies, and the framing is correct.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    22[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    23[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe calibration-matters-as-much-as-discrimination subsection is the recipe's biggest pedagogical contribution and is the lesson most ML-on-clinical-data treatments skip. "A score of 0.6 has to mean '60% chance of deterioration in the prediction window' if the threshold is going to be set sensibly. Models that aren't calibrated produce thresholds that are arbitrary, and arbitrary thresholds produce alert volumes that don't match operational capacity" is the framing every clinical ML team needs. The subgroup-performance-is-operations-work subsection is correct and substantive (continuous, not one-time, with named mitigation paths including subgroup-stratified threshold tuning, subgroup-specific recalibration, fairness-aware training, ongoing audit cycles). The alert-fatigue-is-a-design-constraint subsection is publication-ready and uses concrete numbers (300 inpatients, hourly scoring, 7,200 daily evaluations, 95% specific model produces 360 false positives per day, RRT page every four minutes) to make the design implications obvious; the six design implications (tiered alerting, suppression of non-actionable alerts, differential routing, time-based gating, acknowledgment and feedback, operational threshold tuning) are concrete and operationally actionable.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    24[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    25[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Honest Take is publication-ready and should be preserved verbatim. The eleven lessons (the model is the smaller half; vendor versus build is mostly a false choice; local validation is not optional and is not "we ran AUROC on a hold-out set"; NEWS2 is harder to beat than the literature suggests; calibration is more important than discrimination; alert disposition data is gold and most teams don't capture it well; subgroup monitoring is exhausting and necessary; bedside monitor integration is sometimes worth it and sometimes not; the thing I'd do differently is start with smaller scope; the political reality of clinical staff who are tired of new systems and tired of alerts; the trap of optimizing for the wrong metric; the closing "lives are saved sometimes" framing with explicit reference to Kaiser Permanente AAM and University of Chicago eCART published outcomes) are the right teaching priorities. The closing is the kind of moral-clarity framing that distinguishes the cookbook from documentation: "I want to say this clearly because it's easy to get lost in the operational difficulty: when these systems work, they work."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    26[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    27[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Why This Isn't Production-Ready section is the densest in any chapter-3 recipe with fifteen substantive bullets (clinical governance is the entire program; local validation is non-negotiable; prospective shadow deployment; bedside monitor integration is its own project; alert routing integration; EHR banner integration is vendor-specific naming Epic Cogito and BPA, Cerner Discern, SMART on FHIR; FDA regulatory determination with the 21st Century Cures Act CDS exemption boundary discussion; bias and equity audit framework; decommissioning criteria; patient-facing transparency considerations; vendor handoffs; disaster recovery and continuity; integration with rapid response and code teams; cross-shift handoffs; research-and-quality-improvement use vs clinical use). Each bullet is tied to a real production concern. The "build the governance before the technology" framing on clinical governance is operationally accurate and is the lesson that distinguishes mature programs from immature ones.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    28[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    29[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mStyle hygiene is exceptionally clean: zero em dashes (verified directly with U+2014 character check; zero matches), zero en dashes (U+2013; zero matches), no marketing language, no documentation-voice. The 70/30 vendor balance is preserved cleanly: the conceptual sections (The Problem, The Technology, General Architecture Pattern) are vendor-neutral and a reader on GCP, Azure, or on-premises could substitute their cloud's primitives without rewriting any of the teaching; AWS service names enter at the AWS Implementation section and stay there. Eight HTML-comment TODOs are present, all forward-placeholder for industry-figure verification (NEWS2 and MEWS published operational performance characteristics; current FDA CDS guidance and SaMD applicability with the 2022 CDS guidance reference; specific peer-reviewed evaluations including Wong et al. on EDI, Romero-Brufau et al. on machine-learning EWS, eCART work by Churpek et al., and meta-analyses by Smith et al.; Wong et al. specific JAMA Internal Medicine citation; Amazon Timestream HIPAA-eligibility status verification; HIPAA-eligible Bedrock foundation models list as of current year; aws-samples or aws-solutions-library-samples deterioration-prediction or sepsis-prediction or early-warning-systems repository confirmation; specific peer-reviewed citations for academic literature including Wong et al., Romero-Brufau et al., Churpek et al., Smith et al., Escobar et al. for Kaiser Permanente AAM, and Singer et al. for Sepsis-3; AWS blog posts on clinical deterioration prediction); all are the chapter-2-and-3-settled posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    30[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    31[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe findings cluster into the now-familiar chapter patterns: (1) recurring chapter-wide gaps that are now strong appendix-consolidation candidates (idempotency, DLQs, PHI minimization in alert payloads, subgroup data governance, per-consumer IAM scoping, MLLP and EHR ingress security, Bedrock BAA discipline, VPC endpoint precision, VPC Flow Logs, sample-data staleness); (2) recipe-3.7-distinctive prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetries where The Honest Take and Why This Isn't Production-Ready sections call out specific disciplines (treatment leakage in feature construction, cold-start handling, drift monitoring with calibration drift, shadow deployment as a routing primitive, decommissioning criteria as a governance primitive, vendor handoff data flow) that the canonical pseudocode walkthrough does not reflect; (3) recipe-3.7-distinctive operational-completeness concerns (alert payload PHI surface is unusually large because the explanation contains current and trajectory feature values; bedside monitor integration architecture is acknowledged but not architecturally factored; FDA CDS regulatory determination is acknowledged but no specific architectural primitive supports the determination).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    32[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    33[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThere are no CRITICAL findings and no HIGH findings. The MEDIUM cluster includes outcome-event idempotency at the EventBridge → outcome-capture path (recurring trigger-idempotency pattern, twelfth consecutive recipe with this finding, now firmly cookbook-wide-appendix-priority); no DLQ or poison-message handling for the event normalizer, scoring orchestrator, alert router, or outcome-capture Lambdas (architecturally critical for a system in the result-release-then-alert path of inpatient clinical care, where a dropped vital event is an unscored patient and a dropped alert event is a missed alert); treatment-leakage and feature-cutoff discipline named in The Technology section ("the cleanest mitigations are either restricting the model to features available at decision time only, or framing the problem as causal inference") but not enforced in Step 4's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcompute_features[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m pseudocode; cold-start handling identified in "Where it struggles" as a key failure mode but no architectural primitive in the pseudocode for detecting cold-start state and routing to population priors; alert payload PHI minimization for pager and Vocera and TigerConnect channels (the structured explanation includes current vital values and lab values which is high-PHI; the same chapter-3-settled "event-id-only with fetch-by-id" convention from 3.1, 3.3, 3.4, 3.5, 3.6 should be stated explicitly); subgroup data governance for fairness monitoring acknowledged in prose but architectural artifacts unspecified (sixth consecutive chapter-3 recipe; cookbook-wide appendix candidate); reference-data versioning is partially captured (calibration curve version and threshold set version are explicit per-prediction in Step 5) but the linkage from the alert payload back to the feature snapshot used to produce the score is not enforced as immutable; suppression-rule expiry enforcement primitive missing (Step 7 reads [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mstate.suppression_until[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m but no scheduled job walks the suppression registry for expired entries).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    34[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    35[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mLOW findings are operational and editorial polish: per-consumer IAM scoping for shared resources (patient-state DynamoDB, alert state, scoring history); HL7 v2 / FHIR R4 EHR ingress security posture not specified; bedside monitor integration paragraph in Why This Isn't Production-Ready is correct but no architectural placeholder shows where the bedside-monitor stream would land in the pipeline; Bedrock LLM-explanation BAA-discipline forward reference to Chapter 2's settled patterns; Comprehend Medical nursing-note ingest path PHI handling not specified; HealthLake networking and access control posture not specified; VPC endpoint precision (recurring); VPC Flow Logs not explicitly required (recurring); SageMaker Model Monitor specifics for the calibration-and-subgroup drift pattern named in "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" but not in the architecture diagram; sample timestamps use future dates (recurring); HTML-comment TODOs to resolve before publication (NEWS2/MEWS operational performance, current FDA CDS guidance status, Wong et al. specific citation, HIPAA-eligible Bedrock model list); performance-benchmark numbers should be flagged more prominently as illustrative; FDA SaMD regulatory-determination architectural primitive (a documentation artifact tracked at the model-registry level) not specified.[K
