[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     79[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m "The Technology" Subgroup-Performance-Is-Operations-Work-Not-A-One-Time-Audit subsection; "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" Bias and Equity Audit Framework bullet ("Subgroup performance monitoring needs to be operationalized: which subgroups are monitored (age bands, sex, race and ethnicity where structurally captured, language, insurance status, unit type), which metrics (AUROC, PRAUC, calibration ECE, alert rate, alert disposition rate, time-to-acknowledge), which thresholds for triggering investigation, and which mitigation paths are pre-approved (recalibration vs. threshold adjustment vs. retraining vs. de-escalation)").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     80[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe is unusually clear about subgroup dimensions: age bands, sex, race and ethnicity (where structurally captured), language, insurance status as a proxy for SES, unit type, service line, primary diagnosis, time of day, day of week. The framing ("must monitor performance across clinically meaningful subgroups ... Models that perform well overall but worse on specific subgroups produce harm patterns that map onto existing care disparities") is exactly right. The Why This Isn't Production-Ready bullet correctly names the concrete operationalization: which subgroups, which metrics, which thresholds, which mitigation paths.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     81[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     82[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mBut the architectural artifacts that make subgroup monitoring binding rather than aspirational are not specified: where the demographic and patient-attribute store lives, who has read access, how it joins to alert events and acknowledgment records, what the audit trail for subgroup queries looks like, what IAM scope the QuickSight dashboard role and the retraining job role need on demographic data, and how the dashboard avoids exposing row-level demographic data to dashboard viewers.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     83[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     84[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mRace and ethnicity data has different governance from PHI per se in some regulatory regimes; some state laws restrict secondary use of demographic data more tightly than HIPAA restricts PHI. The recipe's framing-level treatment is correct; the architectural backstop that operationalizes it is missing. Same finding shape as Recipes 3.2 S2, 3.3 S2, 3.4 S2, 3.5 S2, 3.6 S3 (now six chapter-3 recipes deep).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+     85[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add a "Subgroup data access" paragraph or row to Prerequisites: "Subgroup performance and acknowledgment-pattern monitoring requires read access to patient demographic attributes (age band, sex, race, ethnicity, preferred language, insurance type) and unit attributes (unit type, service line). These attributes may be governed differently from clinical PHI in some regulatory regimes (state laws often restrict secondary use of race and ethnicity data); restrict read access to the demographic-and-attribute store to the retraining job role and the fairness-monitoring dashboard role, and audit subgroup queries via CloudTrail data events. The QuickSight dashboard backed by Athena should query an aggregated subgroup-metrics table (alert rate by age band by unit type, calibration ECE by sex, time-to-acknowledge by service line, alert disposition rate by primary diagnosis category), not the raw demographic-joined alert archive, so that dashboard-user access does not require row-level read on the subgroup attributes." Strengthen the IAM row with the per-role scope: retraining job role gets [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mglue:GetTable[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140ms3:GetObject[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m only on the demographic-joined view; fairness-monitoring dashboard role gets read-only on the aggregated subgroup-metrics table. With this finding now flagged across six chapter-3 recipes, the subgroup-governance appendix is the second-highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment alongside trigger-idempotency.[K
