[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    208[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mhas_active_antibiotic[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mhas_active_vasopressor[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mhas_active_opioid[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, etc. medication-class features include any administration in the recent-medication window, including administrations that may have occurred after a triggering event but before the scoring call ran. For an event-driven score that fires on a new vital observation, the medication state at scoring time may include administrations that were given between the triggering event's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mobserved_at[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and the scoring call's actual execution time. This is a subtle form of data leakage.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    209[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrecent_lactate_order[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrecent_blood_culture_order[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrecent_oxygen_titration[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m order-context features are correctly framed in the prose ("New orders ... often precede formal deterioration recognition by hours, because the bedside team is acting on suspicion before they call rapid response. The 'the team has just ordered a lactate' feature is sometimes one of the highest-importance features in production models"). But this same prose names the concern that order patterns reflect the team's clinical reasoning, which is causally entangled with the outcome the model is trying to predict. A model trained with these features and deployed without proper leakage guards will learn "the team ordered a lactate → high risk" which is the right correlation but a fragile one (a hospital that changes its lactate-ordering policy will produce model drift that's not in the patient population).[K
