[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    274[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mMore consequentially: the [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mfeature_snapshot_id[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m link from alert back to feature snapshot is necessary for clinical-safety review (a patient-safety officer reviewing a specific alert needs to know exactly what features were available at the prediction time, and the SageMaker Feature Store with point-in-time correctness can reproduce that snapshot from the snapshot ID). If the alert payload does not preserve the snapshot ID, reproducing the prediction for a clinical-safety review requires correlating the alert by patient and time against the scoring history and then against the feature store, which is operationally fragile and may produce wrong reproductions if the time-correlation is off by more than one scoring tick.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    275[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    276[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mAlso missing: model-monitoring uses the same feature-snapshot trail to detect drift. A model that has drifted produces feature distributions that have shifted; the snapshot-ID trail makes the drift-detection job efficient. Without consistent snapshot IDs in the alert audit trail, drift-detection requires re-fetching feature data which doubles the load on the feature store.[K
