[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    454[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mZero CRITICAL findings, zero HIGH findings (well below the "more than 3 HIGH = FAIL" threshold). The recipe is teaching-strong, voice-clean, and architecturally sound at the conceptual level. The 3:14 a.m. medical-surgical-floor sepsis vignette (the densest sepsis-deterioration framing in any cookbook recipe), the seven-paragraph "the reason the problem is hard" subsection (time is asymmetric; baselines are deeply personal; context is everything; multiple deterioration phenotypes look different; workflow integration is the actual product; regulatory and legal exposure is real; bias and equity are first-order concerns), the track-and-trigger lineage subsection (clinically accurate), the "what ML adds (and where it adds less than vendors suggest)" reframe, the "two big vendor models, and why you should know their reputations" subsection (the cookbook's first published treatment of vendor-versus-build for clinical ML), the eight-method ML survey (the broadest in any chapter-3 recipe), the outcome-definition subsection (unusually substantive), the eleven-feature-class taxonomy, the calibration-matters-as-much-as-discrimination subsection (the recipe's biggest pedagogical contribution), the subgroup-performance-is-operations-work reframe, the alert-fatigue-is-a-design-constraint subsection (publication-ready voice with concrete numbers), the Honest Take with eleven substantive lessons, and the Why This Isn't Production-Ready section's fifteen substantive bullets are all publication-ready. Style hygiene is exceptionally clean (zero em dashes verified, zero en dashes verified, no marketing language, no documentation-voice, 70/30 vendor balance preserved, eight HTML-comment TODOs as forward placeholders).[K
