[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    541[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m##[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mNotes for Editor[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    542[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    543[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThere are zero HIGH findings. The MEDIUM findings cluster across architectural completeness with a heavy prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetry signature: A3 (treatment-leakage discipline), A4 (cold-start handling), A6 (reference-data versioning propagation) are all places where the prose makes a discipline claim that the canonical pseudocode walkthrough doesn't reflect. A1 (idempotency), A2 (DLQs), A5 (suppression expiry), S1 (alert payload PHI minimization), S2 (subgroup governance) are the recurring chapter-wide patterns. The LOW findings cover operational and editorial polish.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    544[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    545[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe two highest-leverage fixes are A3 (treatment-leakage / feature-cutoff in Step 4 pseudocode) and A4 (cold-start detection and routing). A3 is the more consequential because the prose explicitly identifies treatment leakage as the fundamental modeling concern and the recipe's audience includes ML engineers who may construct training datasets based on the recipe's framing; skipping the as-of-cutoff discipline at the feature-engine level produces models with optimistic retrospective AUROC that won't generalize to production. A4 is the right operational mitigation for a known failure mode that the recipe correctly identifies but does not architecturally support.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    546[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    547[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mFinding A1 is the now-recurring trigger-idempotency pattern, surfacing for the twelfth consecutive recipe (2.4-2.10 and 3.1-3.7). The cookbook would benefit substantially from a shared appendix that covers the patterns once. Each subsequent recipe could reference the appendix rather than repeat the discipline. With the per-recipe-edit posture producing diminishing returns, the trigger-idempotency appendix is the highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    548[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    549[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mFinding A2 (DLQs) is operationally critical for Recipe 3.7 specifically because the system is in the alert path of inpatient clinical care and the FDA-CDS-exemption posture depends on the system operating as designed. The DLQ-depth alarm threshold for the event-normalizer and scoring-orchestrator paths should be 1 (single-event sensitivity), not the typical "alert on sustained backlog" pattern.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    550[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    551[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mFinding S1 is the now-recurring PHI-minimization-inside-the-BAA pattern with the seventh distinct surface across the cookbook (Chapter 2 prompts; Recipe 3.1 examiner reasoning; Recipe 3.2 patient-facing reminders for high-stigma specialties; Recipe 3.3 SNS notification payload; Recipe 3.4 SNS interrupt-alert with high-stigma drug class; Recipe 3.5 SNS critical-callback with high-stigma test class; Recipe 3.6 case-ready triage with provider-and-flag-detail sensitivity; Recipe 3.7 alert payload with full deterioration-phenotype clinical narrative reaching pager / Vocera / TigerConnect lock-screen-visible channels). Recipe 3.7's distinctive amplification is that the explanation narrative is itself the PHI-carrying field. A cookbook-wide PHI-minimization appendix would consolidate all seven surfaces with one teaching pass.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    552[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    553[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mFinding S2 is the six-recipe chapter-wide subgroup-governance pattern (Recipes 3.2, 3.3, 3.4, 3.5, 3.6, 3.7 all flag the same shape). Treat the subgroup-governance appendix as the second-highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment alongside trigger-idempotency. Recipe 3.7's subgroup taxonomy is the most comprehensive in the chapter, and the framing-level treatment is the strongest; the architectural backstop is the operational-completeness gap.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    554[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    555[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Honest Take section is publication-ready and should be preserved verbatim. The eleven-paragraph structure (the model is the smaller half; vendor versus build is mostly a false choice; local validation is not optional; NEWS2 is harder to beat than the literature suggests; calibration is more important than discrimination; alert disposition data is gold; subgroup monitoring is exhausting and necessary; bedside monitor integration is sometimes worth it; the thing I'd do differently is start with smaller scope; the political reality of clinical staff who are tired of new systems and tired of alerts; the trap of optimizing for the wrong metric; lives are saved sometimes) is the kind of operations-engineer voice the cookbook is built on. The closing "I want to say this clearly because it's easy to get lost in the operational difficulty: when these systems work, they work. They catch sepsis early, they prevent code blues, they get patients to the ICU before they crash, they save lives" framing is the kind of moral-clarity framing that distinguishes the cookbook from documentation; it should not be shortened.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    556[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    557[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe opening 3:14 a.m. medical-surgical-floor sepsis vignette is the densest sepsis-deterioration framing in any cookbook recipe and should not be shortened. The 32-bed floor, the operational details (charge nurses' patient assignments, shared CNA, 4-hour vitals cadence on stable patients), the post-op day 2 colon resection, the daughter pressing the call button at 1:40 a.m., the recollect vitals, the lactate of 4.2, the broad-spectrum antibiotics at 2:38 a.m., the ICU transfer at 4:15 a.m., the nine extra days of stay and three weeks of inpatient rehab, and the data trail of HR climbing 78 to 92 over eight hours and RR creeping 14 to 18 and temperature rising 37.1 to 37.8 and white count of 14.2 and creatinine 0.3 above baseline and the 9 p.m. nursing note ("patient appears slightly more somnolent than earlier shift, easily arousable") are publication-ready voice and operationally accurate.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    558[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    559[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe "two big vendor models, and why you should know their reputations" subsection is the cookbook's first published treatment of vendor-versus-build for clinical ML. Naming Epic Deterioration Index and eCART by name, naming the Wong et al. external validation study, and the explicit "the right answer for many hospitals is to deploy a commercial model with strong local validation rather than build from scratch" framing is the design lesson most first-time builders miss. This subsection should be preserved verbatim; the V3 fix (resolving the Wong et al. JAMA Internal Medicine specific citation) is editorial polish before publication.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    560[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    561[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe calibration-matters-as-much-as-discrimination subsection is the recipe's biggest pedagogical contribution and is the lesson most ML-on-clinical-data treatments skip. It should be preserved verbatim. The framing ("A score of 0.6 has to mean '60% chance of deterioration in the prediction window' if the threshold is going to be set sensibly. Models that aren't calibrated produce thresholds that are arbitrary, and arbitrary thresholds produce alert volumes that don't match operational capacity") is publication-ready.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    562[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    563[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe alert-fatigue-is-a-design-constraint subsection is publication-ready voice and should be preserved verbatim. The concrete-numbers framing (300 inpatients, 7,200 daily evaluations, 360 false positives per day at 95% specificity, RRT page every four minutes) is the kind of math-meets-operational-reality teaching that distinguishes the cookbook.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    564[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    565[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mStyle hygiene is exceptionally clean: zero em dashes (verified directly with U+2014 character check; zero matches), zero en dashes (U+2013; zero matches), no marketing language, no documentation-voice. The 70/30 vendor balance is preserved cleanly. HTML-comment TODO discipline is correct (eight TODOs total, all forward-placeholder, no bracket-style visible TODOs). The NEWS2/MEWS operational performance, current FDA CDS guidance, Wong et al. JAMA Internal Medicine citation, and HIPAA-eligible Bedrock model list TODOs should be resolved before publication; the forward-looking peer-reviewed evaluations, validated architectures, aws-samples repos, fairness literature, and AWS blog post placeholders read cleanly.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    566[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    567[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mCoordinate with the existing code review ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mreviews/chapter03.07-code-review.md[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m). The code review PASSed with two WARNINGs and eleven NOTEs in the Python companion. The two WARNINGs (non-atomic [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mupdate_patient_state[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m get-then-put with concurrent-event race; eventually-consistent [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mbuild_explanation[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m prior-score query that can produce incorrect [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mscore_change_from_last[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m) are recipe-3.7-Python-companion-only and represent operational-correctness gaps in the Python implementation. NOTE 5 (PHI policy contradiction in the suppression log) is the Python-companion-side analog of this expert review's broader S1 alert-payload-PHI concern. NOTE 6 (three feature-engineering gaps relative to the pseudocode: lab trajectory, hours_since_{class}, recent_oxygen_titration) is a Python-companion-only teaching-fidelity bug; the main recipe pseudocode is internally consistent on these features. NOTE 8 (S3 [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mput_object[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m without [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mSSEKMSKeyId[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m) parallels Recipes 3.1, 3.2, 3.3, 3.4, 3.5, 3.6 and is a recurring chapter-wide pattern that should be addressed with a coordinated fix plus a STYLE-GUIDE.md addition. NOTE 11 (Bedrock model ID hardcoded to two-generations-old Claude version) parallels this expert review's S5 which addresses the broader BAA-discipline-and-prompt-discipline framing.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    568[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    569[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe risk profile is comparable to Recipes 3.4 and 3.5 in autoverification-gating consequence terms (the deterioration system is in the alert path of inpatient clinical care; a missed alert is a missed deterioration; an oversensitive system produces alert fatigue that erodes trust and produces missed deteriorations through the back door). The risk profile is elevated relative to Recipes 3.1-3.6 in clinical-safety consequence terms because the system actively contributes to bedside clinical decision-making rather than supporting back-office operations; and elevated in regulatory consequence terms because of the FDA CDS / SaMD boundary that the recipe correctly addresses. The recipe's prose framing addresses the elevated risk correctly (FDA regulatory determination, prospective shadow deployment, local validation, bias and equity audit framework, decommissioning criteria, vendor handoffs, integration with rapid response and code teams, cross-shift handoffs, research-and-quality-improvement use vs clinical use); the operational-completeness backstops (treatment-leakage and feature-cutoff in pseudocode, cold-start handling, idempotency, DLQs, suppression expiry, reference-versioning propagation, alert payload PHI minimization, subgroup governance, shadow-deployment primitive) are the right next-pass priorities. With those addressed, Recipe 3.7 sits at the same publication-ready quality bar as the strongest Chapter 2 and Chapter 3 recipes.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    570[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    571[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe fairness surface area is unusually substantive: the recipe's subgroup taxonomy (age bands, sex, race and ethnicity, language, insurance status, unit type, service line, primary diagnosis, time of day, day of week) is the most comprehensive in any chapter-3 recipe. The framing ("Models that perform well overall but worse on specific subgroups produce harm patterns that map onto existing care disparities") is exactly right. The architectural backstop (S2) is the operational-completeness gap. The framing-level treatment is the strongest in the chapter.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    572[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    573[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe deterioration-domain authority is the strongest in any chapter-3 recipe. The track-and-trigger lineage is clinically accurate; the vendor-model framing (Epic EDI, eCART, Wong et al.) is unusually current; the ML-method survey is the broadest in the chapter; the outcome-definition treatment is unusually substantive; the calibration emphasis is the lesson most ML-on-clinical-data treatments skip; the FDA CDS framing is unusually current; the Honest Take's references to Kaiser Permanente AAM and University of Chicago eCART published outcomes are clinically accurate and operationally meaningful. This is the strongest single-chapter-3 recipe in domain authority and voice; the editorial pass should preserve as much of the prose as possible while addressing the prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetries (A3, A4, A6, A7) and the recurring chapter-wide patterns (A1, A2, A5, S1, S2, S3, S4, S5, S6, N1, N2, N3).[K
